  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - BARD</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>IMPROVING BRASS</font> - <small>Ysoria Cadenza, Tarew Marr</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><p>I got so much conflicting advice on this topic, I decided to post what finally worked for me. Brass songs are very powerful at the higher levels, but it's hard to get the skill up.<br>
<br>
First, I put about 20 practice points into brass with my guild trainer. That got me to
'average.'&nbsp;<br>
Then I went to Greater Faydark and started singing Denon's Disruptive Discord out in the fields. As mobs drifted into my range they were immediately affected (and killed) by the song, and my skill improved. Of course remember not to wander into the range of things you don't want to attack, like guards.&nbsp;<br>
<br>
Best method: I went to the bandit camp in Greater Faydark and parked myself on the campfire, singing DDD. As the bandits spawned, they were hit by my song, ran away, and died a minute later. The spawn rate is five minutes, so I just stayed there. A few other things wandered into range, too, like bats and spiders. Consider them bonus mobs. (If lower level players come to legitimately hunt the bandits, though, be courteous and let them have the camp. This method can be used anywhere.)<br>
<br>
You can also try sitting down with a friend in a safe place and singing DDD while you sit. The song will
'hit' your friend, without causing any damage, of course.&nbsp;<br>
<br>
What didn't work...<br>
- Singing DDD or fear in a safe place alone. Your song needs to 'hit' something, even if it's a greenie.<br>
- Singing brass songs a lot in combat. I don't know why, but this was just too slow and never got me any skill gain.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
